```csharp
public static void WriteObjectValue<T>(this Utf8JsonWriter writer, T value, ModelReaderWriterOptions options = null)
{
    switch (value)
    {
        case null: writer.WriteNullValue(); break;


```

Checking the switch cases...

If `ResponseError` doesn't implement `IJsonModel<ResponseError>` or `IUtf8JsonSerializable`, then `WriteObjectValue` will fall through and throw. In Azure.Core 1.46.1, `ResponseError` should implement one of these interfaces, so let me try building to verify what's actually happening.

When we call `writer.WriteObjectValue(Error, options)`, the type parameter T gets inferred as `ResponseError`, so the check becomes `case IJsonModel<ResponseError>`. If that interface isn't implemented, the switch falls through to the default case and throws `NotSupportedException`. I should probably revert these calls to use `JsonSerializer.Serialize(writer, Error)` instead to be safer.

```

csharp
JsonSerializer.Serialize(writer, Error);
```

Since `ResponseError` has the `[JsonConverter]` attribute, the serializer can discover the converter at compile time even in AOT scenarios, so the SYSLIB warnings are likely overly cautious. I'll revert the serialization calls and suppress the AOT warnings with a pragma directive.

